1. Features of Waves

Waves are all about transferring energy without transferring matter. Think of a duck bobbing on the water - it moves up and down, but the wave moves past it.

Wavelength (Œª)

The length of one full wave cycle.

The distance from a point on one wave to the same point on the next wave (e.g., crest to crest). Measured in metres (m).

Amplitude

The wave's "height" or intensity.

The maximum displacement of a point on a wave from its undisturbed position. Measured in metres (m). A larger amplitude means more energy.

Frequency (f)

How often a wave passes.

The number of complete waves passing a certain point per second. Measured in Hertz (Hz).

Time Period (T)

How long one wave takes.

The time taken for a single wave to pass a point. Measured in seconds (s).

Period & Frequency

The inverse relationship.

Period is the inverse of frequency. If a wave has a high frequency, it has a short period.

T = 1 / f

Crest & Trough

The high and low points.

Crest: The highest point of a wave.

Trough: The lowest point of a wave.

Wavefronts

Visualising waves from above.

Lines connecting points on a wave that are at the exact same phase (e.g., connecting all the crests). They show the shape of the wave from a bird's-eye view.

(Refer to the diagram showing the labelled features of a transverse wave)

2. The Wave Equation

This fundamental equation connects a wave's speed, frequency, and wavelength. It's essential for solving wave problems!

Wave Speed = Frequency √ó Wavelength

v = f √ó Œª
v = wave speed in metres per second (m/s)
f = frequency in Hertz (Hz)
Œª = wavelength in metres (m)

3. Transverse & Longitudinal Waves

Waves can be classified into two main types based on the direction of their vibrations.

Transverse Waves

The oscillations (vibrations) are perpendicular (90¬∞) to the direction of energy transfer.

Examples:

  • All electromagnetic waves (light, radio)
  • Ripples on water
  • Waves on a string

Longitudinal Waves

The oscillations (vibrations) are parallel to the direction of energy transfer.

Examples:

  • Sound waves & Ultrasound
  • Seismic P-waves

4. Wave Behaviour

Waves don't just travel in straight lines. They can bounce, bend, and spread out. Let's explore how.

Reflection

‚ñæ

Reflection is when a wave bounces off a boundary. The angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection (i = r). The wavelength, frequency, and speed of the wave do not change.

(Refer to the diagram showing reflection of a plane wave at a barrier)

Refraction

‚ñæ

Refraction is when a wave changes direction as it passes from one medium to another. This happens because the wave's speed changes. For example, water waves slow down in shallower water. This change in speed causes the wavelength to change, but the frequency remains constant.

(Refer to the diagram showing refraction as waves pass from deep to shallow water)

Diffraction

‚ñæ

Diffraction is when waves spread out as they pass through a gap or around an obstacle. The amount of diffraction depends on the wavelength relative to the size of the gap. The effect is most significant when the gap size is similar to the wavelength. Wider gaps or shorter wavelengths cause less diffraction.

(Refer to the diagram showing diffraction through different gap sizes)

5. The Ripple Tank

A ripple tank is a shallow glass tank of water used to demonstrate and investigate the properties of water waves.

How It Works

‚ñæ

Setup: A light source above the tank shines through the water onto a screen below. The crests act like convex lenses, focusing light to appear bright. The troughs act like concave lenses, diverging light to appear dark.

Wavelength (Œª): Can be measured by placing a ruler on the screen and finding the distance between two consecutive bright lines.

Frequency (f): Determined by the frequency of the motor that creates the vibrations. A stroboscope can be used to "freeze" the waves to measure f accurately.

Wave Speed (v): Can be calculated using v = f √ó Œª.

Demonstrating Wave Behaviours

‚ñæ

Reflection: Place a straight barrier in the tank. The waves will reflect off it, showing that the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection.

Refraction: Place a shallow glass or perspex block in the tank to make the water shallower. As waves pass over it, they will slow down, their wavelength will decrease, and they will change direction.

Diffraction: Place two barriers to create a gap. The waves will spread out after passing through the gap. The amount of spreading can be observed by changing the gap size.
